sysid 2023 is not working for me. I deployed me robot code and NT was shown connected and then I deployed my sysid settings and it shows disconnected. I found the issue and I downloaded the latest commit from here. It worked and it even showed NT connected after the sysid deploy but here is where the main problem arises. I run the first test and it runs fine but after I end it the NT disconnects and connects over and over and over. I am using two sparkmaxes both update to the latest version and navx-mxp (spi port). How can I fix this?

Have you updated?

FRC 2023 SysID tool issues Control System
I just updated to 2023.2.1 and issue has been resolved. You just have to download 1.8gb for another version of WPILib. I wish they had a way of downloading a small update, but the current way works.

You need to also double check that all computers you’re using have a C++ compiler installed. The C++ add-ins in vscode don’t come with a compiler and it’s needed for sysid.

Akash_Rastogi:

You need to also double check that all computers you’re using have a C++ compiler installed. The C++ add-ins in vscode don’t come with a compiler and it’s needed for sysid.

Can you expand on this more why you say a c++ compiler is needed? The roborio c++ compiler is installed by the wpilib installer. However, it’s not used when running sysid executable. A desktop c++ compiler isn’t installed but also isn’t needed to run the sysid executable (only c++ simulation).

Akash_Rastogi:

We had seen it listed as a requirement in some documentation a few nights ago.

You probably saw this, which is the list of requirements to build SysId.

GitHub

GitHub - wpilibsuite/sysid: System identification for robot mechanisms

System identification for robot mechanisms. Contribute to wpilibsuite/sysid development by creating an account on GitHub.

They aren’t required to run it. The section before it is titled “Building and Running SysId”, but that’s in the context of building and running it from source (the compiler isn’t needed for the running part).

SysId is able to deploy robot programs because it precompiles different variants and embeds them in the SysId binary. A JSON is read at runtime to decide what hardware devices to instantiate.
